{
  "local_port": 38914,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "My Windows 8.1 system is taking unusually long time to start / boot on Lenovo PC .Could there be any solutions?",
  "response": "If your Windows 8.1 system on your Lenovo PC is taking an unusually long time to boot, there could be several reasons for this issue, including startup programs, system configuration, disk health, or software conflicts. Below are some steps you can take to identify and resolve the problem:\n\n---\n\n### 1. **Disable Unnecessary Startup Programs**\n   - Press `Ctrl + Shift + Esc` to open Task Manager.\n   - Go to the **Startup** tab.\n   - Disable programs that are not essential by right-clicking and selecting **Disable**.\n   - Restart your PC and check if boot time improves.\n\n---\n\n### 2. **Run a Disk Check**\n   - Open Command Prompt as Administrator (`Win + X` > Command Prompt (Admin)).\n   - Type the following command and press Enter:\n     ```\n     chkdsk /f /r\n     ```\n   - Restart your PC to let the disk check run. This process can take some time.\n\n---\n\n### 3. **Optimize Your Hard Drive**\n   - Open **This PC**, right-click on your system drive (usually C:), and select **Properties**.\n   - Go to the **Tools** tab and click on **Optimize**.\n   - Select your drive and click **Optimize** to defragment it (if it\u2019s an HDD).\n\n---\n\n### 4. **Update Device Drivers**\n   - Go to **Device Manager** (`Win + X` > Device Manager).\n   - Check for any devices with a yellow exclamation mark, which indicates a driver issue.\n   - Update drivers for critical components like your hard drive, chipset, and graphics card.\n   - You can also visit Lenovo\u2019s support website to download the latest drivers for your PC model.\n\n---\n\n### 5. **Perform a Clean Boot**\n   - Press `Win + R`, type `msconfig`, and press Enter.\n   - Go to the **Services** tab, check **Hide all Microsoft services**, and click **Disable all**.\n   - Go to the **Startup** tab and click **Open Task Manager** to disable startup items (as in Step 1).\n   - Restart your PC and see if boot time improves. If it does, enable services/startup items one by one to identify the culprit.\n\n---\n\n### 6. **Check for Windows Updates**\n   - Go to **Settings** > **Update & Security** > **Windows Update** and check for updates.\n   - Install any pending updates, as they may include performance improvements.\n\n---\n\n### 7. **Scan for Malware**\n   - Run a full system scan using Windows Defender or a trusted third-party antivirus program.\n   - Malware can significantly slow down your system.\n\n---\n\n### 8. **Increase Virtual Memory**\n   - Open **Control Panel** > **System and Security** > **System** > **Advanced system settings**.\n   - Under the **Advanced** tab, click **Settings** in the Performance section.\n   - Go to the **Advanced** tab and click **Change** under Virtual Memory.\n   - Ensure **Automatically manage paging file size for all drives** is checked or manually adjust the size.\n\n---\n\n### 9. **Check BIOS Settings**\n   - Restart your PC and enter the BIOS/UEFI settings (usually by pressing `F2`, `F12`, or `Delete` during boot).\n   - Ensure that the boot order is correct (your primary hard drive should be first).\n   - Check for BIOS updates on Lenovo\u2019s support website.\n\n---\n\n### 10. **Consider Upgrading to an SSD**\n   - If you\u2019re still using a traditional HDD, upgrading to an SSD can significantly improve boot times and overall system performance.\n\n---\n\n### 11. **Perform a System Restore**\n   - If the issue started recently, you can perform a system restore to revert your system to a previous state.\n   - Go to **Control Panel** > **Recovery** > **Open System Restore** and follow the instructions.\n\n---\n\n### 12. **Reset or Reinstall Windows**\n   - If none of the above steps work, consider resetting or reinstalling Windows 8.1.\n   - Go to **Settings** > **Update & Security** > **Recovery** and choose **Reset this PC**.\n\n---\n\nIf the problem persists after trying these steps, there may be a hardware issue (e.g., failing hard drive) that requires professional diagnosis.",
